First rewrite the “fraction‐in‐a‐fraction” as a division problem:  
\[
\frac{\tfrac{2}{x^2-1}}{\tfrac{3}{x+1}}
\;=\;
\frac{2}{x^2-1}\;\div\;\frac{3}{x+1}.
\]

Next multiply by the reciprocal of the divisor:

\[
\frac{2}{x^2-1}\;\times\;\frac{x+1}{3}
\;=\;
\frac{2(x+1)}{3\,(x^2-1)}.
\]

Since \(x^2-1=(x-1)(x+1)\), this becomes

\[
\frac{2(x+1)}{3\,(x-1)(x+1)}
\;=\;
\frac{2}{3(x-1)},
\]

provided \(x\neq\pm1\).  

Answer: \(\displaystyle \frac{2}{3(x-1)}\), \(x\neq\pm1\).

First note that \(x^2-4=(x-2)(x+2)\).  Rewrite the denominator over the common denominator \((x-2)(x+2)\):  
\[
\frac{5}{x-2}-\frac{3}{x^2-4}
=\frac{5}{x-2}-\frac{3}{(x-2)(x+2)}
=\frac{5(x+2)-3}{(x-2)(x+2)}
=\frac{5x+10-3}{(x-2)(x+2)}
=\frac{5x+7}{(x-2)(x+2)}.
\]
Hence the original expression becomes
\[
\frac{\frac{3}{x+2}}{\frac{5x+7}{(x-2)(x+2)}}
=\frac{3}{x+2}\,\cdot\,\frac{(x-2)(x+2)}{5x+7}
=\frac{3(x-2)\,\cancel{(x+2)}}{(5x+7)\,\cancel{(x+2)}}
=\frac{3(x-2)}{5x+7}.
\]
Final answer:
\[
\boxed{\frac{3(x-2)}{5x+7}},\qquad x\neq2,\,-2,\,-\frac{7}{5}.
\]

First note that \(x^2-49=(x-7)(x+7)\).  Rewrite both the numerator and the denominator over this common denominator and then divide:

Numerator:
\[
\frac{2}{x-7}-\frac{1}{x+7}
=\frac{2(x+7)-1(x-7)}{(x-7)(x+7)}
=\frac{2x+14 -x+7}{x^2-49}
=\frac{x+21}{x^2-49}.
\]

Denominator:
\[
\frac{6}{x+7}-\frac{1}{x^2-49}
=\frac{6(x-7)-1}{(x-7)(x+7)}
=\frac{6x-42-1}{x^2-49}
=\frac{6x-43}{x^2-49}.
\]

Hence the big fraction is
\[
\frac{\dfrac{x+21}{x^2-49}}{\dfrac{6x-43}{x^2-49}}
=\frac{x+21}{6x-43},
\]
with the understanding that \(x\neq7,-7\).

